<subsection xml:id="subsec-area-of-an-annulus">
    <title>Area of an Annulus</title>

    <image width="50%">
    <latex-image label="Annulus">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw the outer circle in blue
            \fill[very thick,cyan] (0,0) circle (2);
            % Draw the inner circle in white
            \fill[very thick ,white] (0,0) circle (1);
            
            % Draw radius lines
            \draw[very thick,thick,-&gt;] (0,0) -- (0:1) ;
            \draw[very thick,-&gt;] (0,0) -- (120:2) node[midway, right] {$R$};
            
            % Draw center mark
            \draw[very thick] (-0.15,0) -- (0.15,0);
            \draw[very thick] (0,-0.15) -- (0,0.15);
            
            % Label
            \node[above ] at (0,3) {\textbf{Annulus}};
            
            \node [below]at (0.5,0) {$r$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
        
        
    </image>
    <p>
        This is an Annulus;
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-annulus">
        <statement>
            <p>
                An <m>\textbf{annulus}</m> is the region between two concentric circles (circles that share the same center) 
                with different radii. The area of an annulus is the space enclosed between the outer circle and the inner circle.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Explanation}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                An annulus looks like a ring or a donut shape, where:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>R</m> is the radius of the outer circle.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>r</m> is the radius of the inner circle.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                Since the annulus is just the difference between the two circles, 
                we can calculate its area by subtracting the area of the smaller circle from 
                the area of the larger circle.
            </p>
            
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Derivation of the Area Formula}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The area of a circle is given by the formula:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A= \amp \pi r^2 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The area of the outer circle (larger) is:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A_\text{outer}= \amp \pi R^2 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The area of the inner circle (smaller) is:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> A_\text{inner}=\amp \pi r^2 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The area of the annulus is the difference between the two areas:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> A_\text{annulus}=\amp A_\text{outer}= A_\text{inner}</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \pi R^2 - \pi r^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \pi(R^2-r^2)</mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
        Therefore,
    </p>
    <sidebyside>
        
        <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="Box2">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Formula box
                \draw[very thick,fill=cyan] (3,2) rectangle (8,-2);
                \node[align=right] at (5.5,0.5) {\huge $A = \pi R^2 - \pi r^2$ };
                \node[align=right] at (5.5,-0.5) {\huge $A = \pi (R^2 - r^2)$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
            
        </image>
